<center><table width='90%'><tr><td width='100%' id=MsgBoardGroupTD><a href='msgGroup.asp?Group=1' id=ShowA><font size=2>Back To General</font></a></td></tr></table></center><br><br><br><table width='90%' cellspacing=1><tr><td align=right><a id=ShowA href='replyMsg.asp?message=1553'>Reply</a></td></tr></table><table width='100%' cellspacing=1><tr><td valign=top id=MsgBoardGroupNameTD width=150><center><font color=white>Anonymous</font><br><font size=1>8/29/01 11:01:51 PM</font><br></td><td valign=top align=left id=MsgBoardGroupName2TD><center><font color=white><b>Damn it hurts...</b></font></center><hr>I don't claim to be immaculate, but I also don't claim to be a dog.  As such I don't expect to be treated as either.<br>
<br>
I say many things in jest and I have been known to rub folk the wrong way on occasion.  I take heed of my oversight and do my best to see that it does not happen again.  If I ever mean something, you'll know it from square one.<br>
<br>
When I know that I've screwed up, I apologize.<br>
<br>
I don't like people trying to string me out for something which I *know* they *know* was in jest.  I take it very poorly when someone takes a bite outta my hide for no concrete reason - as though they were trying to place a dark cloud over a friendship.  It sincerely hurts.  Goddamn but it hurts.<br>
<br>
I find myself often taking the hit though for the sake of friendship.  What can I say except that I'm a pushover 99% of the time?  It is part of my long-ingrained belief that I'm the rotten one.  Hell, I'm miserable most of the time, so what does it matter if I add more to my mounting hill of misery so that someone else can remain happy?<br>
<br>
Now, certainly one person can't take too much misery without blowing his damn head off, so I vent.  That vent usually takes form as humor, even if I'm not the funniest person around.<br>
<br>
So when recently a friend took offense to a comment and decided to dangle a sword over my head - the stake being our friendship (a stake so very high for the circumstance, but a stake I did not want to lose) - I decided to take the hit as I usually do when faced with this beast.  <br>
<br>
I apologized.<br>
<br>
With a curt action, I was blown off like so much dust.<br>
<br>
I don't expect folk to warm instantly, but I do like to be given a spark or two so that I know the flame has not died out completely.  No spark this time, just ice.  I'm evidently on the "safe to be hurt - they'll come crawling back" list.  Not that I'm surprised.<br>
<br>
If our friendship was so little that one would risk it over the smallest of remarks and then not even throw a glimmer my way when the olive branch was extended, why should I try to continue it?<br>
<br>
<br>
So I don't.  <br>
<br>
I wish them "a good life" and then I leave.<br>
<br>
...and then I hurt...<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
...<br>
<br>
Because I can't end this post without speaking to the person in question, you were really one of the most pleasant friends I have ever had the priveledge to know.  Your conversation was always welcomed and I'll miss having your presence of character (the human kind, not some virtual rubbish).  I was very happy to have known you, even if only for a year.  I wish you well in your future endeavors and prosperity in your life.  I really thought you knew me better than you seemed to have revealed to me this eve.  <br>
<br>
Finally I hope the knife at least grips well, because the point isn't very comfortable in my gut.<br>
<br>
...<br>
<br>
<br>
